####  Describe the bug

A clear and concise description of what the bug is, including expected behavior and actual behavior

Login with IntelliJ into Azure is not possible: I can login in the web browser, but the credentials are not forwarded to IntelliJ.

I tried: Device Login and OAuth 2.0 methods. Both login fine in the browser, but IntelliJ does not detect the successful login (OAuth) or is stuck at the login. 

Steps tried to fix: 
-Update IntelliJ + all plugins (no success, now IntelliJ is at 2022.1)
-Restarted computer
-Tried to login to azure with "az login" via terminal (login in terminal is successful, but login into shell is not recognized by IntelliJ)

####  To Reproduce

Login to Azure with either OAuth 2.0 or Device Login. 

Steps to reproduce the bug

No exception is visible.

### Actual behavior

I ran the `:config` command and completed the form. The configuration was saved to my pom, but it _also_ removed every blank line on my pom, so I had to go and put these all back manually

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/18747768/161607158-a875a3c8-dba4-43e1-8bce-f9a553d009b8.png)

I don't think it's good for the plugin to change with the pom file like this:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/18747768/161607252-6ca3897d-3f3c-4dc9-b112-fb902326e416.png)

### Expected behavior

Don't remove blank lines from the pom. People use them to help readability in large pom files.

'2022-04-04T07:07:29Z', 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': 'It prompts me to login every time when I run 'mvn azure-spring-cloud:deploy', it seems like it never stores the access token


### Plugin name and version
`azure-spring-cloud-maven-plugin:1.7.2:deploy`

### Plugin configuration in your `pom.xml`

config was done by this
`mvn com.microsoft.azure:azure-spring-cloud-maven-plugin:1.7.2:config`

in pom.xml
```
..
        <plugin>
            <groupId>com.microsoft.azure</groupId>
            <artifactId>azure-spring-cloud-maven-plugin</artifactId>
            <version>1.7.2</version>
            <configuration>
                <subscriptionId>xxxxxxxxxx</subscriptionId>
                <clusterName>spc-krc-001</clusterName>
                <appName>azure-spring-petclinic-simple</appName>
                <isPublic>true</isPublic>
                <deployment>
                    <cpu>1</cpu>
                    <memoryInGB>1</memoryInGB>
                    <instanceCount>1</instanceCount>
                    <runtimeVersion>Java 8</runtimeVersion>
                    <resources>
                        <resource>
                            <filtering/>
                            <mergeId/>
                            <targetPath/>
                            <directory>${project.basedir}/target</directory>
                            <includes>
                                <include>*.jar</include>
                            </includes>
                        </resource>
                    </resources>
                </deployment>
            </configuration>
        </plugin>
..
```

### Expected behavior

### Actual behavior

```
[ERROR] Failed to acquire a new access token.
[INFO] Retry attempts have been exhausted after 0 attempts.
[WARNING] Cannot get subscriptions for tenant xxxxx , please verify you have proper permissions over this tenant, detailed error: Cannot acquire token from refresh token due to error: com.microsoft.aad.adal4j.AdalClaimsChallengeException: {"error":"interaction_required","error_uri":"https:\/\/login.microsoftonline.com\/error?code=53003"}
```
![이미지](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/20915976/146707942-a6bfc5bd-63ab-48ac-85b3-12ecc7088e0b.png)

https://github.com/JetBrains/azure-tools-for-intellij/issues/578 reported by @alexandrunechifor.

---

Importing a Maven(Java) azure function generated with IntelliJ into another instance of intelliJ results in a broken state for the imported project as the function module is not found in run configurations(error: please specify a module).

Steps to reproduce
1)generate an Azure functions project with IntelliJ
2)remove .idea and .iml files - this often happens when committing to git - not everyone is using IntelliJ and these files should not be relevant when someone else tries to import the project, even in another instance of IntelliJ
3) import project in IntelliJ as maven project and experience the following results:
- project cannot be built/run after import from IntelliJ 
- maven cannot find properties definitions
- "module" field is not present and cannot be added when trying to add an Azure Function Run configuration

Being able to import an Azure Functions project independently of the existence of .idea and .iml files is crucial for collaborative development for many teams.
